# Sub-PR design discipline

Multi-round per-trait PRs (RandomX v2 sub-PRs, LWMA-1 Phase 4,
future consensus-critical extractions) accumulate process disciplines
that are not trait-specific. Phase 2c's design rounds (1–5) and the
**pre-flight pass** (disposition IDs **R0-D5–R0-D12** in the 2c audit
trail — "Round 0" in plan-doc naming only, meaning impl-time pre-
flight after design closure, not "the round before Round 1") produced
fourteen named disciplines; they first landed in
`docs/design/RANDOMX_V2_PHASE2C_PLAN.md` and
`docs/design/RANDOMX_V2_PHASE2C_AUDIT.md` and are promoted here so
downstream authors inherit them without re-deriving from one plan-doc.

**Opt-in (same shape as `07-consensus-atomic-cutovers.mdc`).** This
rule is not injected into every session. **Cite
`26-sub-pr-design-discipline.mdc` explicitly** when scoping or
reviewing a multi-round per-trait PR — in the plan-doc scaffold, PR
description, or reviewer checklist. Single-commit additions, doc-only
changes, and refactors outside the scope test below do not invoke it.

Each discipline below follows
`21-reversion-clause-discipline.mdc`'s rejection / reopening criteria /
re-evaluation shape, applied at sub-PR altitude. Inline sub-headers
are intentional for skim-friendliness; the structural inheritance is
explicit here rather than duplicated from rule 21.

**Disposition choice.** Option A — this file — over
`docs/conventions/SUB_PR_DESIGN_DISCIPLINE.md`. The disciplines fit
the project's standard rules shape without needing a separate multi-
page conventions doc. Worked examples cite disposition IDs and the 2c
plan-doc audit trail; this file is the authoritative process surface.

Per `05-system-thinking.mdc`, these disciplines are the operational
form of "specification first, code second" for sub-PR design: the
spec is the frozen contract, the threat-model frame, and the substrate
read — not prose intuition about what the reference "probably" does.

**Numeric claims at pre-flight.** Every numeric claim in a plan-doc —
constants, budgets, LoC envelopes, commit counts — is subject to
verification at pre-flight; the plan-doc records the claim, pre-flight
records whether the claim survived contact with substrate or
measurement. **B6** (R0-D9) is the source-line variant: verify values
against the cited substrate line at audit pin. **B9** (R0-D12) is the
measurement variant: run prescribed benches/tests and reconcile
thresholds against empirical baselines before a budget becomes a
gate — the failure mode where `compute_hash_alloc` measured ~296 ms
against a 100 µs label is only catchable by running the bench, and
generalizes to any budget written from inherited-code intuition
without measuring the Rust implementation on the actual workload.

## Scope

Applies when a work item is split across multiple short-lived PRs
with design rounds before implementation cuts — especially when
consensus behavior, FFI boundaries, or inherited reference ports are
involved. Does not replace trait-specific plan-docs; those carry the
substrate enumeration. This rule carries the *process* that plan-docs
should follow.

## Pre-flight pass (Round 0 disposition naming)

Every multi-round per-trait PR inherits a **pre-flight pass** between
design closure and production code. In plan-doc and audit trails this
pass is labeled **Round 0** and findings **R0-D#** — stable IDs that
must not be renamed. In this rule, **pre-flight pass** is the section
title; **Round 0** / **R0-D#** refer to that same pass when citing
2c precedents.

1. **Substrate re-check.** Re-read the substrate each closed
   disposition cites (source files at audit pin, call graphs, cost
   profiles, established conventions). Catches falsified-justification
   and implicitly-committed-shape dispositions before code lands.
2. **Artifact execution.** Run the tests, benches, and generators the
   plan-doc prescribes; reconcile measurements against budgets at
   PR-open. Catches findings substrate re-read alone cannot surface
   (R0-D10–R0-D12 precedents; B9 above).

The pre-flight pass is **not a redesign**. It catches design-time
decisions falsified by impl-time substrate or by running produced
artifacts. Record findings in the plan-doc status block and in a
sibling audit trail (2c's shape:
`docs/design/<TRAIT>_AUDIT.md`).

**Posture (extends Round 4 / R5-D1).** Design closure means **design
closure plus active defense against named attacker objectives**, not
per-finding whack-a-mole. Pre-flight complements the threat-model
frame: substrate re-check defends against transcription and scope
drift; artifact execution defends against estimates that never met
measurement.

