## Part A — Design-round disciplines

These emerge from adversarial design rounds before implementation.
Apply at round closure and when scoping the next sub-PR.

### A1. Function-body replacement contract

**One-line shape.** Freeze signature + caller state fields + dispatch
input fields; land a NOP or `unimplemented!()` body; the next sub-PR
replaces the body in place only.

**Rejection.** Trait + stub-impl, or signature churn between "extract
surface" and "implement surface," decouples review properties and
invites silent contract drift (new parameters, return values, state
fields added when the body lands).

**Reopening criteria.** Reopen the frozen signature when a downstream
sub-PR's benchmarks or threat-model review shows the single-pass (or
current) shape cannot meet a load-bearing budget **and** profiling
attributes the shortfall to the frozen shape itself — not to missing
implementation. Example: 2c locked single-pass `dispatch_instruction`
(R3-D1 function-body replacement contract); reopen to IBC two-pass
only if 2d benchmarks show single-pass cannot hit the Phase 0 budget
and profiling attributes shortfall to per-call decode cost.

**Re-evaluation shape.** New design-round entry in the downstream
sub-PR's plan-doc naming the frozen surface violated, substrate
evidence (bench profile, threat-model finding), and the amended
contract. Implementation follows in a separate commit sequence per
`90-commits.mdc`.

**Anti-patterns.**

- **"We'll fix the signature when we implement."** The body-replacement
  PR's review surface becomes diff-archaeology instead of mechanical
  contract check.
- **Mock trait for one implementation.** Trait with one impl is debt
  per `21-reversion-clause-discipline.mdc`; use function-body
  replacement instead (F1 / R2-D1).

**Precedents.**

- `dispatch_instruction(instr: &Instruction, state: &mut VmState)` —
  NOP body in 2c (PR #66), body replacement in 2d (R3-D1;
  `RANDOMX_V2_PHASE2D_PLAN.md` contract inheritance).
- F4 absorption: `compute_hash(&Cache, …)` production signature lands
  in 2c; no `DatasetReader` trait + mock.

---

### A2. Audit-against-actual-code

**One-line shape.** Plan-doc audit tables cite pinned line ranges; the
load-bearing step is reading source at those lines, not producing a
plausible table from intuition.

**Rejection.** Audit tables filled from prompted lists, documentation
summaries, or training-data recall without line-range evidence. A
table without citations is a claim that no audit happened.

**Reopening criteria.** Not applicable as a standing rejection — the
discipline is always load-bearing for consensus-critical ports.
**Relaxation** (using uncited tables for non-consensus internal
refactors) reopens only when the changed surface has zero
consensus-affecting consumers and the PR's reviewer-map documents
that exclusion per `07-consensus-atomic-cutovers.mdc` criterion 4.

**Re-evaluation shape.** Reviewer spot-checks cited file at pinned
commit; row fails if cited lines do not support the disposition.
R5-D1 formalized **show your work**: every row names
`path/to/source:N–M` at the audit pin.

**Anti-patterns.**

- **"The table looks plausible."** The mp failure mode: Rounds 1–2
  had `mp` as a `VmState` field; reading `vm_interpreted.cpp:89`
  showed it is a v2-only local alias for `mem.ma` (R3-D1).
- **"We caught one bug, audit done."** R5-D1 reframes: the failure
  mode is skipping reading-the-source — the table is output, not
  substance (`16-architectural-inheritance.mdc` §"audits-are-clean-so-
  compress").

**Precedents.**

- R3-D1 `mp` correction (`vm_interpreted.cpp:89`; not a struct field)
  — consensus-split source if shipped (R5-D1).
- R1-D3 (2d Round 1): wire opcodes are frequency-encoded
  (`bytecode_machine.hpp:67–98`), not `InstructionType` enum values
  (`RANDOMX_V2_PHASE2D_PLAN.md` R1-D3).
- Pre-flight F3 (R0-D1): CFROUND throttle vs non-existent imm32 cap —
  cited `bytecode_machine.hpp:261–266`, not a prompted wrong row
  (`RANDOMX_V2_PHASE2C_AUDIT.md` pre-flight trail).
- R6-D2 (2d Round 6): `RANDOMX_FREQ_*` sums to 256
  (`configuration.h:88–125`, `bytecode_machine.hpp:67–98`), so the
  out-of-range branch in `decode_instruction_type` is unreachable by
  construction. Reading the ladder removed an observable debug-vs-
  release behavior divergence in R1-D3's prior disposition
  (`debug_assert!` / no-op pair) before the §10 equivalence gate would
  have surfaced it. Fourth confirmed instance; reaffirms the
  discipline crystallized at precedent #3
  (`RANDOMX_V2_PHASE2D_PLAN.md` R6-D2).

The four precedents span two adjacent sub-PRs of the same migration
(2c R3-D1 / pre-flight F3; 2d R1-D3 / R6-D2). The discipline is now
load-bearing for any inherited-reference port where prompted summaries
or documentation can diverge from the C reference at the audit pin —
"what the reference is reputed to do" vs "what the reference actually
does at the pinned commit." Treat A2 as non-optional rather than
recommended on that surface class.

---

### A3. Threat-model addenda framing

**One-line shape.** Late-round pass against 3–6 attacker objectives;
route each finding to in-scope absorption, discipline note, or named
downstream forward-action.

**Timing.** Threat-model addenda is typically a **late design-rounds**
discipline (often Round 3–4): after feature completeness, before
closure. At Round 1 the design is not yet stable enough to adversarially
probe; at Round 5-only it is too late — closure means closure **plus**
active defense, not freeze-then-whack-a-mole.

**Rejection.** Closing design on feature completeness without a
priority-1 adversarial pass against named objectives. Per-finding review
misses findings no individual item suggests; the objective frame
clusters them (cache poisoning, FFI exploitation, resource DoS, etc.).

**Reopening criteria.** Skip the threat-model round only when the
sub-PR's pre-flight reviewer-map shows zero cryptographic,
consensus, or untrusted-input surfaces — pure orchestration with no
new attack surface. If substrate later adds such a surface, reopen via
design-round 1 of that sub-PR with a fresh objective enumeration.

**Re-evaluation shape.** New plan-doc section (2c's shape: Round 4
threat-model addenda) with objective table, disposition per finding
`(a) in-scope`, `(b) discipline note`, `(c) forward-action`, and
cross-links in forward-path / target plan-doc scaffolds (A5).

**Anti-patterns.**

- **Per-finding whack-a-mole after "design closed."** Round 4 /
  R5-D1 posture-shift: closure means closure **plus active defense**,
  not freeze.
- **Threat-model findings with no route.** A finding without
  absorb-or-carry disposition is institutional knowledge loss.

**Precedents.**

- Round 4: six objectives → T1'–T8' in-scope; forward-actions to
  2f/2g/3a (R4 §5.11.5–7 disposition IDs in 2c plan-doc).
- R5-D1 ties Objective 6 (consensus split) to audit-against-actual-
  code — threat-model and audit disciplines compose, not duplicate.

---

### A4. Reversion-clause for sub-PR boundary changes

**One-line shape.** Scope moves between sub-PRs need substrate-
anchored reasoning and named reopening criteria; boundary stability
comes from named reasoning, not inertia.

**Rejection.** Silent scope migration (work "was 2e, now 2c") without
documented substrate motivation and reopening criteria. Applies
`21-reversion-clause-discipline.mdc` at sub-PR altitude — cite rule
21 for the three-part shape; do not restate it here.

**Reopening criteria.** A deferred boundary (e.g., "trait stays for
later sub-PR") reopens when a **named production caller** or
**consensus event** requires the abstracted surface now — not when a
contributor prefers convenience or test ergonomics. F4 example: the
absorption removed `DatasetReader` because there was no second
production impl; the trait **reopens** only if a **real production
caller** demands the abstraction (e.g., multiple cache backends in
consensus path) — documented in design-round 1 with call-graph
evidence, not because integration tests want a mock.

**Re-evaluation shape.** Plan-doc section naming old boundary, new
boundary, substrate evidence, parent-plan revision artifact if
phases renumbered, and FOLLOWUPS/CHANGELOG if user-visible scope
shift.

**Anti-patterns.**

- **"The boundary is the boundary."** Refusal-forever without criteria;
  brittle when substrate shifts.
- **Absorb without parent-plan alignment.** F4 required
  `RANDOMX_V2_PLAN.md` phase deletion — scope move plus track
  enumeration update.

**Precedents.**

- F4: `Cache::derive` absorbed from planned 2e into 2c; eliminates
  `DatasetReader` trait + mock (PR #66).
- R2-D1: trait → free function within Round 1 locked dispositions —
  structural tightening, not scope creep (Round 2).

---

### A5. Forward-action propagation convention

**One-line shape.** Every finding routes to **absorb now** or **carry
to named PR scaffold** with the decision recorded in both source and
target docs.

**Rejection.** Findings that live only in a closed plan-doc's prose —
downstream authors re-derive or miss carries. Institutional knowledge
at one-PR-per-contributor risk.

**Reopening criteria.** Inline absorption instead of forward-action
when the downstream sub-PR is **not yet scaffolded** and the work is
≤~100 LoC with zero consensus coupling to the downstream phase —
record the exception in the source plan-doc with why inline was cheaper
than carry. Otherwise carry.

**Re-evaluation shape.** Source: forward-path bullet or Round 4
forward-action subsection. Target: downstream plan-doc §1 or §3
"inherited forward-actions" with ID (e.g., R4 §5.11.6 → 3a FFI
hardening). Close the carry when the target PR lands the work.

**Anti-patterns.**

- **"2d will figure it out."** Without scaffold carry, 2d Round 1
  re-derives FPU, F128, CFROUND pointers from scratch.
- **Carry without target anchor.** Forward-action must name phase +
  disposition ID, not "later."

**Precedents.**

- 2c forward-path: 2d/2f/2g/3a inheritance lists with R4 §5.11.x IDs.
- R4 §5.11.6 → 3a: null-check, length validation, `*const [u8; 32]`,
  `ERR_NULL_PTR` taxonomy — each item copied to 3a scaffold when
  drafted.

